Package software.leonov.common.collect

Class EquivalenceMap<K,​V>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractMap<K,​V>
      • software.leonov.common.collect.EquivalenceMap<K,​V>
  • Type Parameters:
    K - the type of keys maintained by this map
    V - the type of mapped values
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Cloneable, Map<K,​V>
    public class EquivalenceMap<K,​V>
extends AbstractMap<K,​V>
implements Cloneable, Serializable
    A Map implementation which has a predictable iteration order, and allows users to specify their own strategy for comparing keys by providing an Equivalence. Implements all optional map operations. Keys and values may be null.

    Warning: This class intentionally violates the Map contract, which is defined in terms of the hashCode() and equals(Object) operations, and thus should not be considered a general-purpose map implementation. Instead this class is designed for the rare cases when custom equality semantics are required.

    This implementation uses a LinkedHashMap to store key/value pairs, using the provided Equivalence to wrap and unwrap each key as required. This results in a constant, albeit small, performance penalty for most operations. This class has the same ordering guarantees as a LinkedHashMap and provides an identical removeEldestEntry(Map.Entry) method, which can be overridden to impose a policy for automatically removing stale mappings when new mappings are added.

    Providing an equals equivalence will make this class behave identically to a LinkedHashMap. An identity equivalence will make this class roughly comparable to an IdentityHashMap. Care must be taken when implementing an arbitrary Equivalence to ensure it is consistent with itself. That is to say its equivalent(Object, Object) method must be consistent with its hash(Object) method in order for this map to function correctly. This map will be serializable if its keys, values, and the provided Equivalence is serializable.

    This map is not thread-safe. If multiple threads modify this map concurrently it must be synchronized externally.

    The iterators obtained from the entrySet(), keySet(), and values() collection views are fail-fast. Attempts to modify the map at any time after an iterator is created, in any way except through the iterator's own remove method, will result in a ConcurrentModificationException.

    Zhenya Leonov
